Are you saying that this emacs can edit text without vim underneath it, at all ? As in, without keybinds, functions and modes?
That sounds preposterous to me.
If it were true (and I doubt it), then companies would be editing text without a vim. This clearly is not happening, so there must be some error in your calculations. I hope you realise that vim is more than just editing ? Its a whole system that shapes the text from start to finish, and that is a very difficult thing to acheive. A lot of people dont realise this.
Google just spent $9 billion and many years to finally have the creator of vim work for them, so it does not sound reasonable that some new alternative could just snap into existence overnight like that. It would take billions of dollars and a massive effort to achieve. MacroMates tried, and spent a huge amount of money developing TextMate but could never keep up with vim.
Its just not possible that a gnu indention style using program could be extended to the point where it shapes the entire text from start to finish, without using some of the more critical parts of vim. Not possible.
I think you need to re-examine your assumptions. Why else would there be vintage mode in ST or viper in Emacs? You cannot edit text without vim, and that's a fact!
